{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8e59e07d-34c1-434f-a44e-f9b7a47cefc7","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the CPU profiling profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or **Speedscope**.\n\n**To copy it out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Alternatives:**\n- **`dotnet-counters`** — lightweight, good for a quick look at CPU % per-process before committing to a full trace.\n- **`perf`** — if you need OS-level / native call stacks, but requires `SYS_ADMIN` / privileged containers.\n- **Event Pipe via environment variables** — if you can't install tools, set `DOTNET_EnableEventPipe=1` and `DOTNET_EventPipeOutputPath=/tmp/trace.nettrace` then restart the app.\n\nFor most cases, `dotnet-trace` with `cpu-sampling` is the easiest and least invasive option.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"54e871d8-58b0-4b03-ac17-9c59b044e38e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide a concise answer based on my knowledge.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"6086:2DB10D:230F15:2E4E2E:69FFDF77"},"id":"0397323d-49e4-4675-853a-d3d366ef9aa8","timestamp":"2026-05-10T01:29:38.359Z","parentId":"d1f78aa6-ed0a-4475-9db8-3a9c1daaaeff"}
